gomodel:SYNGO_1738  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig. 5D, LTP of synapses between C-fibers and dorsal horn neurons in mice in vivo is impaired in EPHB1 KO mice.\n\nLiteral:\n\"our results showed that targeted mutation of the EphB1 receptor completely abolished the LTP in all mice tested (n = 9) (Fig. 5D). These genetic data strongly suggest that this EphB1 receptor is the specific Eph family receptor critical to and required for development of LTP.\"\n\nFig. 6E-H, high frequency stimulation induced increases of p-CaMKII, p-ERK and p-CREB in dorsal horn neurons is abolished of EPHB1 KO mice.\n\nLiteral:\n\"Further, targeted mutation of the EphB1 receptor completely blocked HFS induced increases of p-CaMKII, p-ERK (Fig. 6E, F) and p-CREB (Fig. 6G, H).\"\n\nand Fig. 7, high frequency stimulation induced increases c-Fos expression is reduced in in dorsal horn neurons is abolished of EPHB1 KO mice.\n\nLiteral:\n\"Similarly, HFS-induced c-Fos expression was significantly reduced by EphB2-Fc (2 μg, from 30 min prior to 3 h after HFS) in WT mice, or prevented by targeted mutation of the EphB1 receptor in the EphB1-/- mice. Representative photomicrographs and the corresponding counts of Fos-like immunoreactive neurons in DH are shown in Fig. 7.. Experimental description: The EPHB1 KO mice were used.\n\nLiteral form M&M:\n\"The generation of EphB1 receptor protein-null mutant mice has been previously described [51,52]. For the present study EphB1+/- heterozygous males and females in the CD1 background were bred to obtain a cohort of homozygous knockout (EphB1-/-) and wild-type (WT) (EphB1+/+) control littermate adult mice (25-30 g-wt).\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2949-9725" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0662-9523" ;
        dc:date           "2017-11-15" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_1738" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

